In San Francisco's 6.9 earthquake, buildings collapsed because of poor soil and structural  design.
Chinatown's unreinforced masonry was thought vulnerable but survived because  of Chinatown's firm soil.
Telegraph, Nob, and Russian Hills, built on rock, escaped  damage.
The Marina District, which lost 60 buildings, is built on landfill dredged from  the bay.
Most vulnerable were four-story apartment buildings with garages across the  bottom, which pitched forward.
High-rises swayed with little damage because of  earthquake codes that demand construction to withstand an 8-magnitude quake with a  San Francisco epicenter.
Earth and wind forces aren't considered as much with smaller  buildings.
Elsewhere, Victorian homes shifted off foundations and chimneys crumbled. 
